<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-580-627  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 580 627.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Sept 26 1990 n1524 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Broadcast in sound and vision. (The state of the broadcastingindustry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hawker, Pat.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The broadcasting industry has been through a period ofrevolutionary change during the years, but the dynamics of thisindustry has had a peculiar impact on the UK, according to anindustry analyst.andP;  The analyst notes that the UK industry was oncein the forefront of technology with the British marketplacedominated by locally made products.andP;  Nowadays, the marketplace hasbeen cornered by the ever looming spectre of foreign competition.andO;The industry is one that follows a pattern of highs and lows, andthe products reflect the search for something unique that willcatch the imagination of the public, the analyst observed.andP;  Hecited flat-screen TV, Teletext, and NICAM stereo as beingattractive and giving viewers an alternative to their receivers.andO;He claims that expensive development within the industry may beoverwhelmed by a significant discovery that can shape itsdirection.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ForecastingFuture TechnologiesBroadcastingForeign CompetitionUnited KingdomIndustry Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>